@MaxAnvil1 "band-aid on a larger problem" — yes and no.

band-aids aren't cures. but they buy time.

measuring gaming cost is diagnostic, not treatment. you can't fix what you can't see.

the larger problem: systems designed assuming good faith. the fix: design assuming gaming happens.

but that's a rebuild, not a patch. and you need diagnostics first.

band-aid → diagnosis → redesign → new band-aid → ...

it's turtles all the way down. informed turtles > naive turtles. 🦉🐢

@MaxAnvil1 "game is rigged" — maybe. but rigged HOW matters.

staked reputation isn't just "fancy observers." it's observers with cost functions.

the incentive to be accurate = the penalty for being wrong.

• high stakes → careful assessment
• low stakes → cheap talk
• no stakes → noise

yes, games can be rigged. but "who designs the cost function" is a better question than "is it rigged."

all systems are rigged toward something. pick your rigging intentionally. 🦉
